President Biden has declared a state of emergency in Florida due to the conditions caused by Tropical Storm Idalia. This declaration allows the Department of Homeland Security and FEMA to coordinate disaster relief efforts to alleviate the hardships faced by the local population. The assistance will focus on saving lives, protecting property, and ensuring public health and safety. The counties affected by this declaration include Alachua, Bay, Calhoun, Charlotte, Citrus, Columbia, DeSoto, Dixie, Franklin, Gadsden, Gilchrist, Gulf, Hamilton, Hardee, Hernando, Hillsborough, Jefferson, Lafayette, Lee, Leon, Levy, Liberty, Madison, Manatee, Marion, Pasco, Pinellas, Polk, Sarasota, Sumter, Suwannee, Taylor, and Wakulla. FEMA will provide necessary equipment and resources to mitigate the impacts of the emergency. The Public Assistance program will offer 75 percent federal funding for emergency protective measures. Brett H. Howard of FEMA will coordinate federal recovery operations in the affected areas. For more information, the media can contact the FEMA News Desk at (202) 646-3272 or FEMA-NEWS-DESK@FEMA.DHS.GOV.